{
  "title": "Amino Acids Momentum Test",
  "publicationStatus": "draft",
  "subtitle": "",
  "fontScale": 0.6,
  "about": [
    "A simple test checking whether the total momentum of each molecule (amino acids chain)",
    "is always equal to zero.",
    "",
    "Amino acids in water or oil are pushed toward the molecule center of mass or in the opposite",
    "direction (it depends on the hydrophobicity of the amino acids). In most cases the sum of",
    "these forces would be different from zero and would cause a confusing movement of the molecule.",
    "They would drift and collide with boundaries.",
    "",
    "To avoid this effect, Next Gen MW modifies velocities of each particle to ensure that the",
    "total momentum of the whole molecule is <b>always</b> equal to zero.",
    "",
    "That's why you can observe that each molecule holds its initial position."
  ],
  "models": [
    {
      "type": "md2d",
      "id": "amino-acids$0",
      "url": "imports/legacy-mw-content/converted/conversion-and-physics-examples/amino-acids-momentum$0.json",
      "viewOptions": {
        "controlButtons": "play_reset_step",
        "modelTimeLabel": true
      },
      "modelOptions": {
        "solventForceFactor": 1.25,
        "additionalSolventForceMult": 4,
        "additionalSolventForceThreshold": 10,
        "polarAAEpislon": -2
      }
    }
  ],
  "parameters": [
    {
      "name": "polarAAEpislon",
      "label": "epsilon",
      "onChange": [
        "var i, j, len;",
        "var polarAAs = [7, 10, 20, 21];",
        "for (i = 0, len = polarAAs.length; i < len; i++) {",
        "  for (j = i + 1; j < len; j++) {",
        "    setPairwiseLJProperties(polarAAs[i], polarAAs[j], { epsilon: value });",
        "  }",
        "}"
      ],
      "initialValue": -2.0
    }
  ],
